European inflation falls on food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro zone, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the Luxembourg statistical office reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not cut the base rate, saying that the reduction, along with rising commodity prices and easing unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but close to, two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is trapped in the 22nd: "to talk down" inflation so that it does not have to act on this subject later.
In Germany, inflation of 3.3% in November is a 12-year record; in Spain it rose to 4.1 from 3.6.
Eurozone inflation has been driven high by rising food and energy prices.
Future wheat quotations have increased by 88 percent, and soybean prices have reached the highest level since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also had to be paid significantly more in 2007.
Oil prices on the world market have increased by 52 percent this year, and last month it cost almost $100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 percent this year to 2.5 percent in 2008, but it will fall to 1.9 in 2009.
Analysts believe that the 12-month inflation rate will remain around 3 percent over the next 3-4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that the ECB has reduced interest rates twice in 2008.
