In many places, disinfectants are saved.
This year, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, mainly due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions of hospitals, the congestion of beds and the overload of staff are not conducive to stopping infections, according to the Chief Medical Officer of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
They also save money on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of John's Hospital.
After a serious accident, a man was found to be resistant to antibiotics.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred earlier this year.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly thereafter he had to return with MRSA infection, and an important surgery has still not been performed because of the bacteria in his body.
By 10 December this year, 1094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, head of department at the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, the rest are unknown.
About two thirds (683 infections) of infections were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried in the nose by one-third of people without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inadequately, the bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop a highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria that spreads rapidly under inadequate hospital conditions.
In particular, if the immune system is temporarily or permanently impaired, it may cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infection or sepsis, in patients with a weakened body, elderly or low body weight.
According to the medical director of János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is just not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not tested.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nursing staff provides the patient with rubber gloves and masks, and they have the right antibiotics for their treatment," Tibor Nyulasi said.
Patients entering the hospital are already tested for MRSA in their body, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
It's not a pattern.
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current domestic hospital conditions and conditions are not favourable to prevent the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, Karolina Böröcz claims.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals, nursing homes, hospitals should monitor incoming patients and immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these studies.
Most cases will come to light if the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the head of department at the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always comply with this.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Saving on Disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transmitted from one patient to another by medical staff.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by droplet infection and contact, but in domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, wards are often crowded, often very close to each other, even though from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, it can also be seen, Karolina Böröcz noted, that hospitals in unfavorable financial situations save on disinfectants, few nurses, many patients, so there is an even greater chance of developing infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are taken, there are fewer such infections or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, so they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, it included the prevention and reduction of MRSA in the government programme.
The programme appears to be successful, with MRSA infections showing a downward trend in England based on the data reported.
Among the priorities of the European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) is the prevention of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
