Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the expert meetings will be completed on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the international climate regime after 2012 will continue with the negotiations of the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts following the emission reduction period set by the Kyoto Protocol to 2012.
At present, there is a heated debate between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not currently wish to discuss precise figures, although it is inclined to agree to a 25-40 percent reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990.
Another big question at the conference is whether developed countries will undertake to provide both financial and technological assistance to countries in need, in addition to reducing emissions.
Agreements have also been reached on aid to developing countries.
The fund, which is part of the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, which is expected to be part of the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF).
6% of Hungary
Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's ambition to preserve its role as a flagship in global climate protection efforts and to promote the establishment of a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to a 20 percent reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the conclusion of the "post-2012 agreement" and is ready to undertake a reduction of up to 30 percent if other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are willing to take on commitments corresponding to their responsibilities and abilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that in 1997 the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol set a total reduction of 5.2%, including the EU - then 15 of its Member States - of minus 8 percent.
The Hungarian obligation is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to the 1985-87 period, which our country will meet. – recalls the press release of the Ministry of Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali, as the long-term international climate agreement must be reached within two years, otherwise its entry into force would certainly be moved after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by another international emission reduction system, the need for which was pointed out by the IPCC, the UN Nobel Peace Prize winner, international scientific body on climate change, in its latest report.
This would result in a delay in reducing emissions and the inevitability of an increase in the Earth's average temperature above 2 degrees Celcius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
