Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Raises Country’s Risk
Founded in August this year with the support of Jobbik Hungary Movement, the activities of the Hungarian Guard increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital.
In its "risk warning", the company wrote that the greatest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that "with the escalation of ethnic tensions already existing between the Hungarian Gypsy and non-Gypsy population, violent ethnic clashes may develop in the short term".
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to be aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this is due to one of the main omissions of Hungarian political actors: "public discussion of Roma affairs has been handed over by public actors to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian conflict".
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard have "significantly worsened the image of Hungary abroad, mainly in terms of faith in the stability and democratic development of the country".
It is recalled that from the autumn of 2006, it has gained increasing publicity and momentum as part of the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, as from the summer of 2007 several organisations calling themselves "national self-defence" associations were formed in Hungary.
“The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as NGOs, while openly promoting the preparation of their members – even armed ones – for defence (disaster protection, defence, law enforcement) tasks, and also on the grounds of the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state,” they added.
They noted that this is done in accordance with the method of putting various political aspirations in a civil guise based on the anti-political and anti-partisanism of society.
Thus, the emphasis on civility and the form of association are not only used to avoid the legal pitfalls of judicial registration in the case of these associations, but also as a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for neighbourhood relations.
In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been referred to as a potential threat in several neighbouring states, and ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so political risks have increased for the region as a whole.
For example, the operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The formation of the Bulgarian Guard is due to the mass Roma riots that broke out in one of the districts of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
BNU used this to decide on the formation of the guard, saying that the purpose of the organization is "national self-defense".
In the last 17 years, Bulgaria has experienced a “gypsy terror”, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent, the Political Capital recalls.
They added that the initiative provoked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As they wrote, the increase in the risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the fact that some Roma organisations in Bulgaria have announced that they will set up their own guard as resistance.
Since the operation of the Hungarian Guard so far shows similarities with the operation of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be excluded that the Roma in Hungary will respond to the threat in the same way by organizing their own self-defense, reads the risk warning of Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, Director of Research at Political Capital, said that risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
He said they would publish their risk analysis annually, and if they experienced anything that could affect the change in risk, they would inform the public, as in this case, by issuing a risk warning.
