Public holidays are mostly linked to church holidays and outstanding historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are both public holidays - the latter just so that New Year's Evers can rest.
There are 11 red-letter holidays throughout the year.
National holiday is also the 15th of March and 23rd of October, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848.
On 20 August we celebrate the founding of the state, on 1 May we celebrate the work, and on 1 and 2 November we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, we have two days of Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or even religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend according to the calendar, it has become a practice to relocate working days in cases where we would only work for one day before or after the red-letter holiday.
True, the price of extended weekends is that we do not stay away from work and school on the previous Saturdays.
The exact date of the day immediately before or after the holiday has been regulated by the Minister of Labour for many years in a separate decree.
The legislation covers all employers and the workers they employ, civil servants and those in a public service relationship.
However, it does not affect service companies and institutions operating without interruption and operating on public holidays as a result of its intended purpose.
This year, the work schedule will only change around the end of the year: from December 24th, life will almost stop in the country, as experience has shown that the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve are "slipped" by the majority of people or use their savings for this purpose.
Next year, we will have more holidays in the middle of the week or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer work shifts than this year.
First, the calendar is transformed around the celebration of work, so that the workers can stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day in exchange for Friday 2 May.
The other relocation is related to the holiday of 23 October: on Saturday, 18 October, it will be necessary to work instead of the 24th of Friday.
However, the end of the year can be fully in the spirit of the holiday next year, as from December 24 there will be a non-stop break almost everywhere, even if New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
