Bury what you have heard, and do not discuss it with your coworkers in absentia, even if others know what your colleague is wearing.
You're calling in sick for no reason?
When you call the office and report a sick person because of a splitting headache because you feel unwell or feel like you would rather rest that day, remember that your work, your urgent tasks, your futures work must be done by someone else for you.
Don't mess with your colleagues.
If you know in advance that you will not go to the office the next day, or that something may happen that will make you stay at home, indicate that your colleagues and boss should not face your absence the next day.
Humping, giggling, making phone calls
You've gone into work, but you're being pulled out of it by the giggles of colleagues?
Have you become an unwitting listener to a phone call that would have been better not to hear?
Do not disturb your colleagues by humming, singing, talking loudly (which you carry over their heads), or by beating their feet, constantly swearing, or being loudly dissatisfied.
These can all be confusing, even if they are not involved in a project (writing, planning, organizing).
Do you blame others for your mistakes?
If something is not timed, you forgot to send an important letter, a message, and don't blame anyone else for your forgetfulness.
Do not refer to the chaos that may prevail in the office, your loud colleagues.
Admit it if you made a mistake, and someone else is at a disadvantage, and eliminate the damage.
Ask how you can make up for your mistake.
Do you feel at home in the office?
Bear pants and slippers: comfortable to wear at home, but not in the office!
Don’t wear comfortable clothes even if your job allows it.
Don’t be sloppy and respect yourself by going into the office in ordinary clothes, if your job requires it, neatly and elegantly.
