Spectacular improvements to the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) had to work more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of the torn solar panel essential to the scientific activity of the station.
This dangerous space walk proved to be a record in several ways: the repair took a very long time, there was very little time to design it, and it had to be done away from the housing modules with tools "made" by astronauts.
The problem arose on Tuesday when astronauts separated the Harmony module from Discovery. It is a giant cylindrical element that will soon be the site of scientific laboratory activities in Europe and Japan (see box).
This module is a kind of gateway to laboratory modules.
However, their power supply must be ensured.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move one of the modules producing electricity with the help of 17,5 tonnes of solar panels, which was already on the ISS, to its final place.
Then the crew began to open the module’s 76-metre wide solar panels.
This is when one of the harmonica foldable boards was damaged by a stuck cable of about 1 metre in length.
In order to avoid further damage, the table was not opened.
Astronauts were originally tasked with taking a tour of the Discovery shuttle and then repairing another solar panel with a faulty rotation system. Instead, they had to devote their entire time to repairing the damaged solar panel.
Scott Parazynski was chosen to perform the stunt by hanging on the 30-metre robot arm attached to the station crane.
He's one of NASA's best space walkers.
Tall, strong, extremely skillful, muscular upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old man had to “operate” the “damaged” solar panel.
After thoroughly assessing the damage, he cut the faulty cable and fixed the damaged area with a few "rails".
He was assisted by another "spacewalker" who stayed close to the safe passage, as well as the other astronauts inside, including the captain of the crew, Peggy Whitson.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick with insulation against hundreds of volts of solar panels, was invented and "made" by the station's astronauts.
After the operation was completed, Scott Parazynski waited for his companions to open the board completely, and then he packed up his tools and returned to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts took a half-day break, and today, seven of them returned to the Discovery shuttle to begin their planned return home on Wednesday.
EADS shares fall in price
The price of EADS shares fell sharply on the Paris Stock Exchange after the aircraft and defense equipment company announced that the delay in the development of the A400M aircraft would result in an additional cost of EUR 1.2-1.4 billion.
The price of EADS shares is currently at EUR 21.96 after a 4% decrease.
The company was forced to review its forecasts for operating profit in 2007, as the development of the A400M engine was delayed, which obviously delayed the delivery of the aircraft.
The delay in the delivery of the tactical transport aircraft, which was announced in October, will cost between EUR 1.2 and 1.4 billion, of which more than 1 billion will be affected by Airbus," the parent company of the European EADS manufacturer announced.
As a result of these expenses, EADS will have to publish new plan numbers for its 2007 operating profit next Thursday, when it announces its quarterly results, the company added, but did not publish any further figures.
The group also indicated that it had taken account of the six-month delay in preparing its new cost estimate.
In 2006, EADS' operating profit decreased by 86%: this was largely due to a delay in the development of another programme, the A380 giant machine, which also placed a heavy financial burden on the company.
The company originally planned to hand over the A400M to the French army in October 2009.
The status quo remains.
Sunday’s elections are not a big surprise: the vast majority of Russians will vote for President Putin’s party, the United Russia.
In this, the Russians' need for stability, as it were, arbitrary governance, is manifested after a powerfully manipulated campaign.
Today, three days before the parliamentary elections, Russian President Vladimir Putin speaks to voters through public service channels in a television message, which has already been recorded, but its content is still secret.
Putin is leading the candidate list of the pro-Kremlin party, United Russia, which is expected to win an overwhelming victory in the elections.
At the reception of foreign ambassadors yesterday, the head of state's behavior did not reveal anything: he only launched another outburst against the interventions of Western countries, which was a popular theme during the campaign.
“We know the price of true democracy, so we want honest, absolutely transparent and open elections without any violations,” he said.
However, according to the opposition, this is not the case.
The opposition condemns the campaign, which they believe has put pressure on voters.
The leader of the Communist Party, Gennady Zjuganov, claims that "such a dirty election in Russia was not even in Yeltsin's time".
After last weekend's protests, former World Chess Champion Garri Kasparov was sentenced to five days in prison for unauthorised protest, and his lawyer claims he still can't be visited.
"The Russians are still thinking 'homo sovieticus'"
Predictable election results raise two more obvious questions:
Who is following Putin in the head of state?
The official paper published yesterday the date of the first round of the presidential election, which will be 2 March 2008, and candidates can indicate their intention to run until 23 December.
Since Vladimir Putin was elected in 2000 and 2004, his mandate can no longer be extended.
There are no other successors on the horizon.
What role will Putin play in March?
Will he be Prime Minister?
Or will he, as the leader of the all-powerful United Russia party or the parliamentary majority, decide on the government and the president?
Either way, the outgoing power wins both parliamentary and presidential elections.
Now it has become a tradition.
"The Russians are still thinking like 'homo sovieticus': they don't feel like they can control their fate," says Lev Gudkov, a sociologist and director of the independent Levada Center.
Nikolai Koposov, historian of the University of St. Petersburg, goes even further: according to his theory, the country became a Christian five hundred years later than Europe, so the development of civil society is also delayed.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, "Putin went back to the paternalist model, which was perfect for the people. All the more so, because this new paternalism was associated not with intimidation, but with certain economic prosperity," says Maria Lipman, a member of the Carnegie Foundation.
Today, the Russians "willfully reject personal responsibility", which was quickly manifested after the dissolution of the Soviet Union.
"Why should we think?"
The phenomenon affects all sectors of society, even the business world.
The administrative elite is interested in maintaining the current situation: the local lists of the United Russia are led by 65 governors, who come from the leaders of the 85 Russian regions.
And freedom imported from the West often embodies chaos, as it did in the 1990s.
Public opinion prefers stability.
In this spirit, the Russians do not vote for extremist parties.
Tamara Cherednychenko, a 54-year-old teacher, concludes: "Why should we think?
Those in power are not so bad, so why should we replace them?"
Repressive Memories
After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive has become public, documenting the fate of the 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archive documents, which occupy 27 kilometers of shelves in Bad Arolsen, Hessen Province, have so far only been researched for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. they have only provided unique and named access to former victims or their descendants.
The eleven states managing the archives, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to open the archive to researchers and historians in May 2006.
After all states ratified the Convention, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen Archives allows historians to conduct research “on the relocation of prisoners, the residents of camps and the health of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the publication of documents, as they contain names and thus confidential information.
This may include, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
The lists of concentration camps and the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons, with the aim of searching for civilians deported or sentenced to forced labour and possibly providing evidence of their internment, which allowed them to receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are currently dealing with tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, part of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of paramount importance.
“These documents are basically nothing new,” said Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Antisemitism Research at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
EU and India to sign free trade agreement in 2008
The annual turnover of Indo-European bilateral trade is already close to EUR 60 billion.
The EU is India's number one trading partner and accounts for 18% of its external trade.
The European Union and India hope to sign the free trade agreement in 2008, European Trade Commissioner Peter Mandelson and Indian Trade Minister Kamal Nath announced.
EU foreign ministers approved in April last year that the European Commission would open negotiations for free trade agreements with India, South Korea and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN). The annual turnover of indo-European bilateral trade is already close to EUR 60 billion.
The EU is India's number one trading partner and accounts for 18% of its external trade.
The EU is also India's main foreign investor, but India is only the EU's 9th most important trading partner according to the European Commission's figures.
Mr Mandelson said: “A free trade agreement can be an economic boost for both sides, and India could increase its presence in a thriving market of 450 million people.”
Europe is the primary or secondary importer of the ten most important products exported by India, the European Commissioner added. The two giants, Europe and Asia, exchange "EUR 47 billion worth of products" and "EUR 10 billion worth of services" each year, said Dani?le Smadja, head of the European Commission delegation in New Delhi this week. At the same time, he regretted that bilateral trade in New India "has still not reached its full potential".
(Source AFP)
Bank of England pledges 10 billion pounds to the financial market for a five-week term
The Bank of England wants to alleviate the unrest over credit conditions, so on Thursday it announced that it will pump ?10 billion into the financial market, which it will make available with a base rate of 5.75% and, unlike usual, a five-week maturity.
“We want to alleviate the concerns that the financial market conditions will be particularly bad at the end of the year, and we also want banks to be able to plan their liquidity positions more safely for this period. Therefore, a significant part of the Bank’s reserves will be offered on the international money market as part of a five-week open market operation from 6 December,” the bank said in a press release.
According to the bank’s announcement, a 10 billion pound (EUR 14 billion) will be placed on the market on 6 December at 12:15 local time. The offer is subject to the central bank base rate and the repayment deadline is 10 January.
This is the first time the Bank of England has issued liquid funds in an open market operation for five weeks.
The duration of such operations is usually one week.
In a press release, the Bank of England added that it was "ready to take further measures" to ensure that interbank loans were aligned with the central bank base rate.
The current interbank interest rate was 5.829% on Wednesday.
The three-month interest rate exceeded the level of 18 September: it is currently at 6.6%.
Since the beginning of the summer financial market crisis, the Bank of England has charged significant punitive interest on the amounts pumped into the financial market, which has deterred banks from using them.
Rumor has it that (which is only reinforced by the exchange rate of the pound against the euro) many would have preferred the resources offered by the European Central Bank, which could have been obtained at a more favourable interest rate and with greater discretion.
UMP and NC refuse to examine socialist proposal on purchasing power
The UMP and the Nouveau Centre group on Thursday refused to discuss the articles of the socialist bill on purchasing power, which is equivalent to rejecting the text itself.
The text discussed at the meeting initiated by the Socialists contained about ten measures, which were adopted on Tuesday by the National Office of the Socialist Party, including, for example, a 50% increase in the employment allowance, the restoration of a variable fuel tax, the introduction of travel cheques and the restriction of rents.
As UMP and NC voted against the articles in 180:115, the sometimes sharp-sounding discussion between the governing party and the opposition was finally interrupted, just a few hours before President Nicolas Sarkozy's television speech on purchasing power.
The head of the Socialist delegation, Jean-Marc Ayrault, announced that he would resubmit all the proposals of his group in the framework of the amendment of the corrective draft financial law, which will be placed on the agenda of the Parliament next week.
A new festival is born
There were many rumors about the new music festival in Philadelphia organized by C3 Presents. However, now the company organizing and promoting the event announced that the Vineland music festival will be held in New Jersey in cooperation with the British producer Melvin Benn, Festival Republic.
"We are honored to work with a man who is the starter of today's American festival movement," Charlie Jones of C3 told Billboard.com.
C3 also organizes the Lollapalooza Festival in Chicago and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
The Vineland Festival in New Jersey will be held in the summer, so there will be room for camping.
The festival will take place between 8 and 10 August in a private area of 500 acres about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
Festival Republic director Melvin Benn, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, is one of the most respected festival organizers in the world.
He started organizing the British Reading Festival in 1989, which attracts about 80,000 visitors every year.
In 1999 Melvin Benn continued to expand his palette by organizing the Leeds Festival, and in 2006 the Festival Republic launched the Latitude Festival in Henham Park, Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn has been co-owner of the Glastonbury Festival's production, license management and organizational tasks. This festival is now able to accommodate up to 177,500 people.
Charlie Jones of C3 called Glastonbury Festival the "most inspiring event" he ever attended. He added that his company and Melvin Benn's company are working in parallel to enrich the region with a European-style festival event.
“The Philadelphia location has already been selected and we have worked hard with the Fairmount Parks Commission to host this festival in the center of Philadelphia,” said Charlie Jones.
“We had a discussion with the city and the Commission showed great enthusiasm for our plan.
Unfortunately, due to the political maneuvers of the city administration, the organization failed," Charlie Jones continued.
“Fortunately, we were able to talk to Melvin Benn about this, and now we are preparing to host a huge festival at another unique venue that will ultimately serve the interests of the people of Philadelphia.”
C3 Presents brought the Lollapalooza festival back to life in 2005 in Grant Park, Chicago, after proving its exceptional talent as a festival organizer with the Austin City Limits music festival in 2002.
The gross revenue of the two events was $9.8 million and $11.3 million in 2007.
Both festivals were held on a city site.
“Melvin Benn’s European concept is based on the country festival, while our festivals usually take place in urban green areas,” says Charlie Jones.
Our goal is to combine the two models in some way to create both the European rural atmosphere and the American urban lifestyle."
Vineland is located about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
“The people of Vineland, and even the mayor himself, are enthusiastically supporting the event,” says Charlie Jones.
Although he does not talk about the details of the agreement, he says that "the conditions are favourable enough to allow investment in such an event at a location that hopefully will host the festival for a long time".
According to Charlie Jones, the festival will be "giant" in size, with a capacity of about 80,000 people at the Bonnaro music festival in Tennessee.
The bands have already been invited to the event, but nothing is final at the time of the press release.
“Vineland is basically going to be a rock festival, but we’re planning a variety of music offerings so everyone can find something to enjoy,” says Charlie Jones.
Jones and his two partners, Charlie Walker and Charles Attal, form the C3 company, which received the "best independent event organizer" award at the recent Billboard Touring Awards.
