Russia-Ukraine gas dispute concerns
The gas price dispute between Ukraine and Russia has been renewed, which may also affect Russian fuel to be transported to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is channelled through Ukraine, and disputes between the two nations are always under close scrutiny.
Kiev said that if Moscow increases the gas price to be paid by Ukrainians, they will also impose higher transit costs on Russia.
As a result of a previous dispute between the two countries last year, supplies to EU countries decreased.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow relates to the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom's attempt to reach an agreement on the level of gas prices to be paid by Ukraine to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom has stated that it will have to increase its gas production from neighbouring Turkmenistan by 50% compared to the price agreement with Ukraine for 2008.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% price increase for Ukraine's shipment from Gazprom.
“It is important that during the negotiations we argue in line with one of the most important transit states for natural gas,” Ukraine’s Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told Reuters.
“The changes to gas prices should certainly be linked to our debate on the extent of the costs of transit through Ukraine (and into Western Europe).”
As a result of the recent significant gas price dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom blocked the gas tap leading to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like reduction in exports to Western Europe, which also greatly pushed prices up.
Russia accounts for a quarter of the EU’s gas supply.
Russia has the world's largest natural gas reserves, but most of them are still unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
The NHS is “obliged to monitor foreign workers”
Scottish NHS committees need to improve the control of criminal records of workers from outside Europe, a supervisory body said.
The proposal came after a foreign national doctor in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland does not have accurate data on the number of employees overseas.
However, in its report, through a sample of five health authorities, it also pointed to key controls that were properly implemented.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the Auditor General checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep hit the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors questioned by the Old Bailey court in October on the charge of car bombing attempts in the UK.
The NHS Committees must verify the skills and work experience of the workers concerned and their authorisation to work in the United Kingdom before starting employment for their employees from overseas countries.
Although Scottish Health Committees use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency is not authorized to obtain such information from outside the UK.
Among other things, the Chief Accountant's report suggested that the committees introduce the Criminal Records Office's guide, which facilitates the employer's control processes with different overseas countries.
"Although there is evidence of such checks in the personnel records, they are not carried out on a regular basis," the report said.
Black said that while the Scottish NHS is performing its own pre-employment screening process at a high level, he added: "Our report highlights the areas of the system that can be improved in order to keep up-to-date on the number of NHS personnel from overseas."
According to Dr. Peter Terry, President of BMA Scotland, it is "extremely unrealistic" to use pre-employment checks to identify potential NHS employees who may commit terrorist acts in the future.
“According to the report, the pre-employment checks currently in place in NHS Scotland are working well, and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent,” he added.
According to Scottish health authorities, the current number of their overseas employees, mostly doctors and nurses, is 1161.
However, the chief accountant drew attention to the fact that the figures are likely to be higher, which is partly due to the fact that committees have a problem identifying employees on permanent leave.
The investigation has also shown that the control procedures in the Ayrshire and Arran regions, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and the NHS authorities in Lothian are highly coordinated.
These procedures covered the verification of passports, work permits and qualification documents.
The Scottish Government is currently examining a policy and guidance on pre-employment inspections of NHS employees from overseas countries.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was very pleased that this task was carried out after the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He also added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, will take into account the proposals in the report and will ensure that the updated guidance on pre-employment checks for the entire staff, including those from overseas, reflects best practice. The updated version is planned to be published next month.
