Venus' climate could give us a glimpse into the future of the Earth
According to scientists, Venus once provided pleasant living conditions.
Data from a European orbiting spacecraft suggest that this planet is more of an Earth's whimsical twin than we previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet neighbor to Earth.
The size of the two planets is almost the same and their orbits are similar, although Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
According to scientists today, billions of years ago Venus could have had very similar living conditions and even habitable conditions.
However, due to the extremely high carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion caused by solar radiation and the planet's lower rotation speed, Venus has entered a very different development path.
Today, the water has evaporated from the planet, its surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is destroyed by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express space probe, based on a year's study of the planet, paint a sobering picture of how similar catastrophic climate changes can develop on Earth.
Fred Taylor, professor of physics at Oxford University, who is also one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It's starting to show why Venus' climate differs so much from Earth's experience, despite the fact that the two planets are very similar.
“With our new data, it has been possible to develop a scenario for the formation of Venus billions of years ago, when it may have had habitable conditions like Earth.
