Card Sharks
Is the second-market mortgage crisis threatening America's credit card market?
When blood enters the water, it is natural for sharks to appear nearby.
Now that the U.S. housing market is failing, predators are focusing on the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts believe that if the mortgage crisis infects other forms of retail credit, the loss of the credit card market could reach $99 billion.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
Both the write-down rate showing the ratio of non-recoverable loans and the default rate indicating the ratio of late payments over 30 days have increased.
HSBC reported a $1.4 billion loss in the U.S. consumer finance segment last month, partly due to the financial weakness of cardholders.
However, panic is still early.
The rates of write-offs and late payments remain low.
The late payment rate of 3.89% calculated by Moody's credit rating agency for the third quarter is one full percentage point lower than the historical average.
The decline in rates can partly be explained by technical factors.
The amendment of the US rules on individual insolvency in 2005 resulted in a sharp decrease in the number of insolvency applicants, while at the same time causing a large loss on the credit card market; the number of bankruptcy applications (and thus the write-down rate) is expected to increase again, regardless of whether the totality of the borrowing conditions deteriorates or not.
The payment rate, which shows the rate of monthly credit repayment by consumers, is also solid in the market.
In addition, trust in credit-card-backed securities is quite strong, despite the paralysis in other areas of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney at TowerGroup estimates that the 2007 emissions volume will be 25% higher than last year.
The impact of the mortgage crisis on the credit card market is clear: consumers are increasing the debt on credit cards to repay home loans.
At the same time, card issuers primarily monitor financial flows and not asset values, and therefore the fall in housing prices does not necessarily result in a change in the creditworthiness of borrowers.
Creditors may benefit from the situation.
If the property is worth less than the value of the mortgage loan, consumers will have a reduced incentive to repay the loan; as a result, the repayment of debts on credit cards will move forward in the priority ranking.
By changing interest rates or lending limits, card issuers can adapt to changing conditions faster and more flexibly than mortgage lenders.
Theoretically, this should reduce the risk of sudden re-prices of assets.
“It’s unlikely that we’ll wake up one day to completely revalue our loans,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a subprime-like sudden crisis in the credit card market is less likely, the risk of a gradual decline is more likely.
If falling housing prices and falling lending push America into recession, the industry will no doubt face a grim future.
