Venus is the Earth's evil twin.
Despite the harsh atmosphere of Venus, it is more similar to Earth than it has been assumed: in its atmosphere, the European "Venus Express" space probe discovered lightning discharges and wind turbulences such as those produced on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that Venus is lightning.
The European "Venus Express" space probe provided evidence - it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at a height of 56 kilometers, reports Christpher Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the columns of the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "old soup theory", the formation of life on Earth was caused by lightning: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If life ever existed there, it could have been in very early times," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
At present, there can hardly be a living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperature values sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but it's her twin," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different path of development.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus research, because since the early nineties, no probe has been specifically on its way to find this planet.
The latest research results presented in several "Nature" articles, according to researchers, do not only prove the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also point out that the similarity of the neighboring planet to Earth is greater than we initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known Arctic whirlwind, researchers also discovered a much faster moving cloud vortex in the South Pole.
The phenomenon reminds me of the air currents of the Earth's winter hemisphere, according to the research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system is almost the same mass as the Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, it is almost the size of the Earth.
The celestial body, also called the Evening Star, orbits the sun in less than 225 days.
However, it turns much slower around its own axis: a Venus day lasts 243 earth days.
Although Venus' surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius, coupled with a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets were created under completely similar conditions.
Both of them had accumulated water, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while on Venus it left for the universe.
And while on Earth carbon dioxide was bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus it forms a large part of the atmosphere.
