These aren't Warhol's crates.
Anyone who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden crates is thinking of Ikea, not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden crates manufactured in Sweden cast a dark shadow on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "Stockholm-type" Brillo Boxes listed in this are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the originality of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Boxes a few months ago, the internal investigation of Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now reached a sobering result: The six "Brillo Box" copies donated to Moderna Museet by Pontus Hulten, former museum director in 1995 - and most likely the round hundred more "Stockholm types" in the international art market.
The history is a confusing chain of long and complicated artistic and board stunts.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxes" in New York in 1964 - painted wooden crates based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the "Brillo" soap powder.
At an exhibition of his works held in Moderna Museet in 1968, hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard were exhibited with Warhol's consent: they did not come from Warhol (for cost savings reasons), but were transported directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It wasn't about works of art, it was about their templates, simple exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited in Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of the age are now talking about fifteen crates that were then certified as Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box under the designation "Stockholm type" rightfully entered the history of art and auction.
Some of them were auctioned off for over $100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hulten, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred wooden crates were manufactured and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol left to him.
In fact, Hulten's 105 crates were only manufactured in Malmo in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time, however, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, chief memorialist of Moderna Museet, examined three Swedish private boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: The pressed chipboards were first ground and sanded, and then the white oil paint was applied with a brush.
On the other hand, the structure of the copies from 1990 shows that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without foundation - and it is not even an oil paint, but an acrylic paint.
"These boxes are not authenticated by the artist, so they should be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brillo Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "Unless the New York 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
The Authentication Board, of course, announced in June that it would investigate the "serious accusations" of soap dust crates.
Since then, however, they have been enveloped in inexorable silence.
